    • Method Detail

      • array

        public static <E> Argument<E> array(TypeCaster<java.lang.String,E> caster,
                                    int min,
                                    int max)
        Build an array argument. With such an argument, the user can input several items for this argument (as a list).
        The minimum and maximum count for the array can be defined, if the user does not respect them, an error message is automatically shown.

        The arguments parsing for this list stops if:
        • There are no more arguments to parse
        • The maximum arguments has been reached
        • A marked option is found (see MarkedOption)
        Type Parameters:
        E - Type of the elements
        Parameters:
        caster - Caster of the elements
        min - Minimum elements accepted for the array
        max - Maximum elements accepted for the array (or -1 for no limit)
        Returns:
        The argument in which the user data will be stored

      • array

        public static <E> Argument<E> array(TypeCaster<java.lang.String,E> caster,
                                    int min,
                                    int max,
                                    E... def)
        Build an array argument. With such an argument, the user can input several items for this argument (as a list).
        The minimum and maximum count for the array can be defined, if the user does not respect them, an error message is automatically shown.

        The arguments parsing for this list stops if:
        • There are no more arguments to parse
        • The maximum arguments has been reached
        • A marked option is found (see MarkedOption)
        Type Parameters:
        E - Type of the elements
        Parameters:
        caster - Caster of the elements
        min - Minimum elements accepted for the array
        max - Maximum elements accepted for the array (or -1 for no limit)
        def - Default values that will be used if the user does not provide them (must respect the above limits)
        Returns:
        The argument in which the user data will be stored

        Type Parameters:

        Parameters:

      • getValue

        public Type getValue()
        Get the value associated with this argument.
        In the case of an optional argument that the user did not input, this will return null (or default if set).

        This should be used only for single element arguments (where max = 1). Else, use getValues()
        Returns:
        Value associated or null if no value is set

      • getValues

        public java.util.List<Type> getValues()
        Get the list of values associated with this argument.
        If the minimum is 0 and no elements have been input by the user, this will return null (or default if set).

        Returns:
        The list of values associated with this argument
